Red Wines Exploration by Natalia Lokshina

This report explores a dataset containing properties of almost 1,600 red wines.

Our dataset contains 1,599 observations of red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine and 1 variable on quality. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Lets look at the distribution of the individual variables.

From this bar plot we can see, that more than half of the wines in our dataset got quality rating 5 or 6. None of the wines were rated lower than 3 and higher than 8.

The distributions of the fixed acidity and volatile acidity are right skewed. They both have a noticeable pick: fixed acidity somewhere between 6.5 and 8.5 and volatile acidity between 0.3 and 0.7. Since the distributions look similar, it will be interesting to see if these variables are correlated.

# calculate the amount of values = 1, 0 and < 0.05 (1st bin)
print(dim(df[df$citric.acid == 1,]))
## [1]  1 13
print(dim(df[df$citric.acid == 0,]))
## [1] 132  13
print(dim(df[df$citric.acid < 0.05,]))
## [1] 274  13

The citric acid distribution looks multimodal with the biggest pick close to 0 and the other 2 about 0.25 and 0.5. There is one outlier with the value 1. Also out of 274 values less then 0.05, which fall into the first bin, almost half (132) have value 0. I wonder if they represent missing data and not the actual level of citric acid.

On the residual sugar histogram we can see a few outliers which give the distribution a big right skew. Let’s zoom in.

The distributions of free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide also look very similar. They are both right skewed. The free sulfur dioxide values lie between 1 and 72 with half of them between 7 and 21 and median 14. The total sulfur dioxide values have minimum of 6 and maximum of 289. There are few outliers close to 289, but 75% of the values are less than 62. I would expect these two variables to be correlated.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

Density looks normally distributed. The mean and median are almost identical: 0.9967 and0.9968. Interesting to note that all values lie in a very small range: 0.0136. Interquartile range is just 0.0022.

The distribution of pH is also close to normal with mean = 3.311 and median = 3.310.

From this histogram we can see that sulphates distribution is right skewed. There are a few outliers close to 2.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

The alcohol distribution is again right skewed. The lowest level of alcohol is 8.4 and the highest is 14.9. Most of the wines have alcohol level somewhere between 9.5 and 11.5.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 red wine observations with 12 variables:

  • fixed acidity
  • volatile acidity
  • citric acid
  • residual sugar
  • chlorides
  • free sulfur dioxide
  • total sulfur dioxide
  • density
  • pH
  • sulphates
  • alcohol
  • quality

All variables have numeric values. Quality is the only categorical variable which has values between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Other observations:

  • The citric acid distribution looks multimodal with the biggest pick close to 0 and the other 2 about 0.25 and 0.5.
  • The distributions of the fixed acidity, volatile acidity, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, sulphates and alcohol are right skewed.
  • The distributions of density and pH are normal.
  • The quality levels are between 3 and 8. Most of the wines have quality rating of 5 and 6.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature is quality. I want to see if any of the provided chemical properties correlated with the quality rating.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

So far it is difficult to say which features are going to be correlated with the quality of wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created a factor variable from quality. It will help me in bivariate exploration section.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I noticed that out of 274 values of citric acid less then 0.05, which fall into the first bin, almost half (132) have value 0. I think they represent missing data and not the actual level of citric acid.

Here we can see that there are no strong correlations between any variables. Some variables moderately correlated. The strongest relationship is between fixed acidity and pH (-0.683). Let’s look closer.

Earlier I was wondering if fixed acidity and volatile acidity are correlated. We can see now that they have weak negative correlation (-0.256). But both of them have moderate correlation with citric acid.

We can see that fixed acidity and citric acid have positive moderate correlation (0.672), and volatile acidity and citric acid have negative moderate correlation (-0.552).

As I expected free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide have moderate positive correlation (0.668). The higher level of free sulfur dioxide, the higher level of total sulfur dioxide.

Now I want to look what has correlation with quality.

According to these data quality is moderately correlated only with volatile acidity and alcohol. The smallest correlation is with residual sugar.

These two plots support the correlation coefficient we got earlier (-0.391). In boxplot we can also see lack of correlation quality rating 7 and 8.

Multivariate Plots Section

On this scatter plot we can see the same result as earlier. The citric acid is higher for higher values of fixed acidity and lower values of volatile acidity.

Here we can see lack of correlation between free sulfur dioxide or total sulfur dioxide and quality. For each quality level there is the same pattern of relationship between free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide.

On this plot dark blue points are mostly on the bottom part of plot. That means that there is a negative correlation between volatile acidity and quality, which we had shown earlier. Also we can see a weak negative correlation between fixed acidity and volatile acidity.

Looking at scatter plots of fixed acidity and volatile acidity separately for each quality level it seems that correlation between them is stronger for quality rates 7 and 8 than for quality rates 4, 5 and 6.

Reflection

Our dataset contains 1,599 observations of red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine and 1 variable on quality. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). More than half of the wines in our dataset got quality rating 5 or 6. Surprisingly, none of the wines were rated lower than 3 and higher than 8. So we don’t have very excellent wines or very bad wines in the dataset. Quality is moderately correlated only with volatile acidity and alcohol. The smallest correlation is with residual sugar.

I struggled with finding strong correlations between quality of wine and its chemical properties. Also I had problem predicting any correlations based on Univariate Analysis. Maybe it happened because of lack of knowledge in chemistry. In future work I would research more on that topic. After plotting a correlation matrix, I quickly found variables with relationship.
